Because `Effect.scoped` wraps the generator, the lock is always released — even if the critical section throws.

```ts
import { Effect, Fiber } from "effect";

const leftE: Effect.Effect<number> = Effect.succeed(21);
const rightE: Effect.Effect<number> = Effect.succeed(21);

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const f1 = yield* Effect.fork(leftE);
  const f2 = yield* Effect.fork(rightE);
  const a = yield* Fiber.join(f1);
  const b = yield* Fiber.join(f2);
  return a + b;
});

Effect.runPromise(program).then((n) => console.log("sum:", n));
```

`Effect.fork` returns `Effect<Fiber<A, E>, never, R>` — forking never fails, only the fiber itself can. `Fiber.join` awaits completion and re-exposes the `A/E` channels.

`Brand.nominal<T>()` is a zero-runtime-cost identity function — it trusts the caller that the value already satisfies whatever invariant the name implies. `Brand.refined<T>(pred, onErr)` runs `pred` at construction and emits a `Brand.BrandErrors` on failure.

Use `nominal` when the invariant is enforced elsewhere (parser, DB constraint, prior validation). Use `refined` when this call site is the first place the invariant is checked.

